Defining neighbours, weights

Lets create two highly contrasting scales of neighbours: very local (1-NN) to very wide (2xmax.dist).

# convert sf to spatial to use spdep
nc_sp <- sf:::as_Spatial(nc$geom)


# k nearest neighbours
# knearneigh() creates matrix with index for the regions belonging to knn
# knn2nb() creates neighbourhood list
sids_kn1<-knn2nb(knearneigh(coordinates(nc_sp), k=1, RANN=FALSE))
plot(nc_sp, main="knn-1")
plot(sids_kn1, coordinates(nc_sp),add=TRUE,col="blue")

# create row standardized weights
sids_kn1_w<-nb2listw(sids_kn1, style="W")

  • We see that the distance matrix with more connections (and reaching a wider distance) are not indicating that there is spatial autocorrelation in SIDS rates, but the local 1-NN does indicate there is spatial autocorrelation.

  • The test for spatial autocorrelation with Morans I is not an exact test, it is approximate.

  • Using moran.mc() we can examine Morans I under randomizing (1000 times) the SIDS79 rates in the nc counties. The red line is placed at the observed Morans I, and the

# Permutations, can save each randomization I and plot distribution
moranSIDS_mc<- moran.mc(nc$SID79/nc$BIR79,sids_kn1_w, nsim=999) 
moranSIDS_mc$statistic
## statistic 
## 0.3003284
moranSIDS_mc$p.value
## [1] 0.006
# res are the 1000 simulations under randomization
distr999<- hist(moranSIDS_mc$res,freq=TRUE,col="light blue",main="Permutation Test for Moran's I - 999 permutations",breaks=75)
lines(moranSIDS_mc$statistic,max(distr999$counts),type="h",col="red",lwd=2)

  • Determining at what lag structures we see significant spatial autocorrelation we generate correlogram plots to see what distance matrix produces significant Morans I

  • The first correlogram type, using sp.correlogram() from the spdep library, takes a nb object, order, and method (I for Morans). It uses row standardized weights as a default and computes I under randomization. The plot is the spatial lags from the original nb object. For example, queen first order lag is the immediate neighbours; 2nd lag is the neighbours of neighbours; 3rd, etc.

  • The second correlogram type, using correlog() from the pgirmess library, takes only the sp object and the number of neighbour classes. It computes all distances between areal units and classifies them into nbclass groups by breaking 0 to max dist into equal nbclass groups. If we want small distances we need to increase the number of distance bins (e.g.nbclass=30 vs nbclass=10).

  • The second distance method not optimal for irregular areal units, better for grids

sids_nb_queen<-poly2nb(nc_sp,queen=TRUE)
corrneigh<-sp.correlogram(sids_nb_queen, nc$SID79/nc$BIR79, order=15, method="I", style="S",zero.policy=TRUE)

Local Moran I

  • Moving to local indexes of spatial autocorrelation we can first look at a Morans I scatterplot, which can pinpoint outliers by dividing the Morans I into quadrants

  • We also directly compute the Local Morans I

mscat<-moran.plot(nc$SID79/nc$BIR79,sids_kn1_w, zero.policy=T, pch=16, col="black",cex=.5, quiet=F, labels=as.character(nc$NAME), main="Moran Scatterplot")

# Plot counties that are in different quadrants of High-Low SIDS and Low-High SIDS
infl<- apply(mscat$is.inf, 1, any)

# Make break points for sids rates and lagged sids rates

# Break rates into low and high
sids79_LH_breaks <- cut(nc$SID79/nc$BIR79, breaks=c(min(nc$SID79/nc$BIR79), mean(nc$SID79/nc$BIR79), max(nc$SID79/nc$BIR79)), labels=c("L", "H"), include.lowest=TRUE)

sids_lag <- lag.listw(sids_kn1_w, nc$SID79/nc$BIR79)

# Break lagged rates into low and high 
sids74_lag_breaks <- cut(sids_lag, breaks=c(min(sids_lag), mean(sids_lag), max(sids_lag)), labels=c("L", "H"), include.lowest=TRUE)
# Make quadrants LL,LH,HL,HH
lhlh <- interaction(sids79_LH_breaks, sids79_LH_breaks, infl, drop=TRUE)
# Identify low-low, low-high, etc colours
cols <- rep(1, length(lhlh))
cols[lhlh == "H.L.TRUE"] <- 2
cols[lhlh == "L.H.TRUE"] <- 3
cols[lhlh == "H.H.TRUE"] <- 4

col.palette <- colorRampPalette(c("white","orange", "red"), space = "rgb")
plot(nc_sp, col=col.palette(4)[cols], main="Morans I")
legend("bottom",horiz=TRUE , legend=c("None", "HL", "LH", "HH"), fill= col.palette(4), bty="n", cex=0.8, y.intersp=0.8)

Getis-Ord G*

  • There is a global version of the Getis-Ord G* statistic, obtained using globalG.test()

  • The local version uses localG(), which returns an object containing the Z-scores for the local G* statistic. The interpretation of the z-score is straightforward: a large positive value suggests a cluster of high SIDS rate (hot spot) and a large negative value indicates a cluster of low SIDS rates (cold spot).

  • G* local uses binary weights recall that the Getis-Ord G statistic differs from Morans I or Geary C in that it makes a difference between high-high correlation and low-low correlation (both of which Morans I treats as positive autocorrelation)

#global
sids_kn1_b<-nb2listw(sids_kn1, style="B")
getisSIDS<-globalG.test(nc$SID79/nc$BIR79,sids_kn1_b)
getisSIDS

# local

sids_kn1_b<-nb2listw(sids_kn1, style="B")
nc_sp$GstarSIDS<-localG(nc$SID79/nc$BIR79,sids_kn1_b,return_internals=TRUE)

# Graphing the G-stat
col.palette <- colorRampPalette(c("blue","orange", "red"), space = "rgb")
gstar_breaks <- c(min(nc_sp$GstarSIDS), -2.58, -1.96, -1.65, 1.65, 1.96, 2.58, max(nc_sp$GstarSIDS))        
col_ramp <-col.palette(length(gstar_breaks))   

# picks colors corresponding for each interval 
plot(nc_sp,border="lightgray",col=col_ramp[findInterval(nc_sp$GstarSIDS,sort(gstar_breaks))])

# maps the shape file and fills each polygon with a color corresponding to the level of G at that location
text(coordinates(nc_sp)[,1],coordinates(nc_sp)[,2], round(nc_sp$GstarSIDS, digits=1), cex=0.5)  
# writes the G-statistic in each polygon
legend("bottom",horiz=TRUE,legend=(round(gstar_breaks,digits=4)),fill=col_ramp,bty='n',cex=0.5)
title("Getis-Ord G statistic for SIDS rates")
